source: # Spotify Songs that won the Grammy Awards
Ruibo Zhang
# Overview

This project aims to see if the nominees for the 2021 Grammy Awards are a representative sampling of songs from the rest of the songs that came out in 2020, using Spotify as our source of data for songs and attributes related to those songs. The results concluded that no discernible difference between the two groups could be found.

# Research QUESTION
What features distinguish the 2021 Grammy’s Awards nominated songs of the year from the rest of the songs released in 2020 in the United States?

# Background & Prior Work
All of us enjoy listening to music, whether it is through Spotify or other similar platforms, but we found this question to be interesting because some of our members play instruments and have background knowledge on basic music theory. This question is also important because music producers would have to choose a key for their song to be in, so our analysis may assist in this part of the music production process. Additionally, an analysis of the relationship between musical keys and song nomination can maybe document the current zeitgeist that may change if this exact analysis is run in a different year.

We know that C major and G major are not only the two most popular keys to play but also the easiest to play across many instruments. Therefore, we figure that they would be the most prevalent among the popular songs. We also know that C major is the most basic key (no sharps or flats) and easiest to play and sing, so we figured that it would be the most prevalent among songs in Spotify. Because C major is likely going to be the most prevalent key, maybe the mere-exposure effect can come into play, and songs with less familiar key signatures are probably going to have more niche audiences. According to [Gizmodo's chart of the most commonly used keys in songs on Spotify](https://io9.gizmodo.com/a-chart-of-the-most-commonly-used-keys-shows-our-actual-1703086174), the proportion of songs on Spotify that are in C major is actually the second highest, falling short on that of songs in G major.

TechXplore experiments with four different models that are trained using [Spotify data to predict what songs will be considered hits](https://techxplore.com/news/2019-09-spotify-songs.html): logistic regression, neural network, a support vector machine (SVM), and a random forest (RF) architecture. Though the SVM model achieved the highest precision rate of 99.53%, the RF model achieved the highest accuracy rate of 88% and highest recall rate of 85.51%. TechXplore proposes that music producers who want to take more risks in producing more hits can use the RF model and those who want to take less risks while still producing hits occasionally can use the SVM model. Additionally, Tim Clements experiments with four different regression models that are trained using [Spotify data to predict the number of followers a Spotify playlist will garner based on song-level categorical features and quantitative audio features](https://github.com/tclements/Spotify-Project): KNN, Ridge, gradient boosted, and multi-layer perceptron (MLP). Based on cross validation scores, the gradient boosted model performs the best, with a score of 0.55. The model does a good job overall but struggles with playlists with a low follower count. In general, Spotify playlists contain songs of similar genre and other key features, and a playlist with a high follower count may contain songs that are very popular, with some that are worthy of a GRAMMY nomination. Our analysis will explore the key features that distinguish the GRAMMY-nominated songs on Spotify from the rest that are released in 2020.

The Grammy nominees are held in high regard and be a showcase what the year has to offer in regards to musical offerings. As such, we felt it would be interesting to compare what gets nominated for the main category and see how representative or non-representative it is to all the songs released that year.

# Hypothesis
We know that C major and G major are the most popular keys, and they are also the easiest to play across most instruments. Therefore, we figured that key signature would be the most distinguishing feature between GRAMMY-nominated songs and the rest of the songs in 2020.
Because C major and G major are basic keys, which feature no flats or sharp keys (or in familiar terms, black piano keys), they are both easy to work with and very common in Western music compositions.
If something is so common, this probably means that it works in some way.

# Dataset The original dataset is obtained through Spotify's Web API. It contains songs released in 2020 and their relevant information/attributes. The dataset contains 32309 samples, each containing 13 attributes.
The dataset is further divided into songs that were nominated as song of the year in the 2021 GRAMMY Awards and songs that did not. In total, 15 songs were nominated, 32294 songs were not. Since both types of songs are obtainable through Spotify's API, we would like to analyze their attributes.
In our study, only 9 out of 13 attributes are used, which are listed as follows:
| Variable Names | Types | Definition | | --- | --- | --- | |popularity|int|The popularity of a track is a value between 0 and 100, with 100 being the most popular. The popularity is calculated by algorithm and is based, in the most part, on the total number of plays the track has had and how recent those plays are.| | key | int | The estimated overall key of the track. Integers map to pitches using standard Pitch Class notation . E.g. 0 = C, 1 = C♯/D♭, 2 = D, and so on. If no key was detected, the value is -1.| |acousticness|float|A confidence measure from 0.0 to 1.0 of whether the track is acoustic. 1.0 represents high confidence the track is acoustic. | |danceability|float|Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. A value of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable. | |energy|float|Energy is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. For example, death metal has high energy, while a Bach prelude scores low on the scale. Perceptual features contributing to this attribute include dynamic range, perceived loudness, timbre, onset rate, and general entropy.| |liveness|float|Detects the presence of an audience in the recording. Higher liveness values represent an increased probability that the track was performed live. A value above 0.8 provides strong likelihood that the track is live.| |loudness|float|The overall loudness of a track in decibels (dB). Loudness values are averaged across the entire track and are useful for comparing relative loudness of tracks. Loudness is the quality of a sound that is the primary psychological correlate of physical strength (amplitude). Values typical range between -60 and 0 db. | |speechiness|float|Speechiness detects the presence of spoken words in a track. The more exclusively speech-like the recording (e.g. talk show, audio book, poetry), the closer to 1.0 the attribute value. Values above 0.66 describe tracks that are probably made entirely of spoken words. Values between 0.33 and 0.66 describe tracks that may contain both music and speech, either in sections or layered, including such cases as rap music. Values below 0.33 most likely represent music and other non-speech-like tracks. | |valence|float|A measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry).| Our dataset differs greatly from what our ideal dataset would be. We are at the whims of Spotify's song features, and our analysis is just limited to songs that we were able to pull from Spotify. To make this even worse, Spotify's API recently limited their search querys to a maximum of 2000 songs at a time, greatly limiting the ease at which a comprehensive list of yearly songs can be pulled from the API. To get around this, we had to pull songs using every single letter or numeric search query, which still capped out at 2000 songs for some of the queries. The list of songs in our dataset is still sizable and should cover a decently representative sample of songs released to Spotify this year, but is still flawed, given how we interacted with the API to obtain the data. Songs that strart with numerals or uncommon letters, like "z" may be overrepresented in our dataset over songs that start with more common letters, like "s" or "t", as these songs are more likely to cap out the 2000 character limit and also show up in multiple search queries, making the search limit per search likely way less than the ideal 2000 that the Spotify API allows. Still, the dataset should be robust enough and should cover enough of the year's releases to not skew the data too much. One thing to note is that the search seems to favor more popular songs, making this dataset underrepresent songs with very few listeners.

# Data Cleaning

- From the data description page of Spotify API, wefind that the data is clean overall as it does not have null values and each variable is well defined in the form of int or float.
- Based on the variable description page of Spotify page for developers, we determine there is nothing special we need to do. 
- In order to compare between songs that have won the 2021 Grammy Awards and the songs that did not, we need to select all the songs that have won from the total song list and do the comparison. We will also be tracking the data distribution in the EDA process.

data_2020 = pd.read_csv('2020spotify_results.csv')
data_2020 = data_2020.dropna()

def is_grammy(string_name):
    #lowercase
    string_name = string_name.lower()

    grammy_2020_list = ['black parade','kaydence','caso','the box',
    'cardigan','circles','don\'t start now','everything i wanted',
    'i can\'t breathe','if theworld was ending']

    #save desired rows, make others null
    if(string_name in grammy_2020_list):
        return 'Grammy'
    else:
        return 'None'

#extract grammy data from dataset
grammy_2021_data = data_2020
grammy_2021_data ['name'] = grammy_2021_data['name'].apply(is_grammy)
grammy_2021_data = grammy_2021_data.dropna()

#Drop useless columns
data_2020 = data_2020.drop(['mode','artists','id','type','uri','track_href','analysis_url','instrumentalness'], axis=1)
grammy_2021_data = grammy_2021_data.drop(['mode','artists','id','type','uri','instrumentalness','track_href','analysis_url'], axis=1)
#dropped 'instrumentalness' because no song that won Grammy is instrumental

# Data Analysis
### P- value comparison

Randomly sampled the same number of observations from the first group and do the comparison, (for the comparison, we used t-test to compare mean of the 2 datasets). Recorded the results. Repeat the process for  many times to see how consistent the results are
The feature selection is based on fomer result of boxplot

sig_fea = []
# place all the p values in each rows into a 9*100 list
result_lst= np.zeros((9,1000))
for col,j in zip(features,range(9)):
    for i in range(1000):
        s1 = df_n.sample(n = 15)
        result = stats.ttest_ind(s1[col],df_g[col])
        result_lst[j][i] = result[1]
#Computed the average of each p-value 
for k in range(9):
    p_avg = sum(result_lst[k])/len(result_lst[k])
    print(p_avg)
    if p_avg < 0.05:
        sig_fea.append(features[k])
print(sig_fea)

By computing the average of the p-values in 1000 iterations, we can roughly observe that it is most probable that only "popularity" and "danceability" can distinguish a song that won the Grammy Award and one that did not.

"Popularity" is kind of a given, as the Grammy's would not nominate a song that people have not heard of for the main category.

The rest are not statistically significant on their own, and it would be disingenous to consider the dancability a statistically significant result given we have not taken any measures to prevent p-hacking. The fact that the Grammy songs lay within the rest in Principal Component 1 paints a better picture that the Grammy's group of songs are not special.

The set of Grammy's songs can not be said to be non-representative of the rest of the dataset, therefore we fail to reject our null hypothesis that we would be able to distinguish the set of Grammy nominees from the set of songs released this year based on key. Even farther, there seems to be no set of features that can classify Grammy nominees from the rest of the songs that came out on Spotify in 2020. This does not mean that the Grammy's songs are a representative of the whole list of songs, however, it is more likely that our statistical tests did not have enough power, given the limited pool of Grammy nominees to reach a statistically significant finding with ease.

# Ethics & Privacy

We have permission to use data provided by Spotify's API and the list of the GRAMMYs 2021 nominated songs because they are publicly available for use. However, Spotify has a [terms of service for developers](https://developer.spotify.com/terms) that users must comply with, but this is not a major concern for us since we are only analyzing the features of songs available on Spotify. Likewise, the GRAMMYs has a [terms of service for all users](https://www.grammy.com/legal), and we comply with Section 10.2 regarding prohibited usage since we are only obtaining one webpage of data.

Spotify provides their data in a processed form; the song title, artist(s), contributors, and numeric features are provided for each entry. This raises concerns on how they quantify certain features of each song; by reducing songs down to numbers, our analysis of these numbers might send a message that opposes the artists' intentions with their work since more experimental songs may be less popular than songs that follow certain trends and dampens their creativity since they are more inclined to only write music that follows the features of popular songs. Additionally, according to [KommandoTech's Spotify user statstics](https://kommandotech.com/statistics/spotify-user-statistics), Spotify's userbase is dominated by millenials and people in their mid-twenties to mid-thirties, so we are unable to generalize our findings to the broader music industry and must be careful with our conclusions. However, this lessens worries about privacy concerns on our end since they are already handled by Spotify, and we only analyze a subset of what Spotify provides.

The GRAMMYs provide raw data; only the song title, artist(s), and contributors are provided for each nomination. However, GRAMMY nominees might not want their listeners to overthink about their music such as analyzing features of their songs that may have factored in their nomination and comparing them between different songs to determine why some songs were nominated and others were not. Simply put, these artists would rather want their listeners to simply enjoy their music. Additionally, the GRAMMYs can be interpreted as a popularity contest, so artists that are well-established in the music industry may have more nominated songs than those who are less popular. Our analysis goes against the intentions of nominated artists, and we have zero control over these biases, so we must be careful in how we present our analysis by not objectively concluding why one song got nominated and why another song did not.
# CONCLUSION & DISCUSSION:

#### Project discussion Our project seeks to explore which features can possibily distinguish songs that have won the Grammy Awards from songs that have not won the Grammy Awards for songs released in 2020. Our objective is different from the former regression models built by researchers to predict the number of hits or the number of followers a song will get. To make our goal more specific, Our group has limit the scope of our data to only songs released in 2020, which include songs that won the 2021 Grammy Awards. We obtained our data through Spotify API to make sure all our data are relevant to our research goal.
#### Analysis Description Our analysis is largely dependent on the exploratory data analysis section. By visualizing comparisons of variable distribution through boxplot and visulizing correlation between variables through heatmap and visualizing comparison of medians, we learn about which variables can possibily contribute to the differnce between two types of songs(Grammy/not Grammy) To mathematically compute the significance of difference in mean of the two types of songs, we further performed t- test on randomly sampled 15 songs from songs that did not win the Grammy Awards (1000 times) and songs that won the award. (reconcile data size difference) #### Conclusions Based on the data exploration and data analysis we performed, we find that there are indeed attributes that can possibily help distinguish songs that have won the Grammy Awards. That is, the attribute "dancibility" based on the t- test. However, the distinction is really small. Moreover, with regards to our hypothesis about key signature, we found no significant difference between the keys of two types of songs. This may be because key signature has too much variation among Spotify songs or it is not really important for people who do not know this concept. #### Limitations Our analysis is only on songs that are released in 2020 and thus the result is not applicable to songs that are released in other years or outside of Spotify. The data for songs that have won the Grammy Awards is limited because of its nature and thus we cannot promise the accuracy of our analysis. The Spotify API is limited in the information we are able to pull. #### Impact on Society Our study on the distinction between Songs that have won Grammy Awards and songs that have not may help people understand how Grammy Award winners are determined. It may also direct artists to a path that can make their songs more popular(i.e.)have higher "danceability" level on Spotify.
